div.pre: Portion of rows with null values: 0.03%

ul.li: Kernel density estimation is used to estimate the probability density function from their respective histograms
Most of the features appear to have a bi-model distribution, and yet there are 3 species

div.h2: Here we can see that most of the attributes are bi-modal without taking 'sex' into account¶
div.p: Hypothesis: Could indicate sexual dimorphism is responsible for the first three features (bill length, bill depth and flipper length)

ul.li: However body mass index appears to be 'almost' tri-modal (you can see about 3 bumps)
There is indeed sexual dimorphism at play
But when controlling for gender, there are still multi-modalities
At least two classes seem linearly separable
Thus, the remaining class must be quite similar to one of the others in terms of its moments or at least defined over a subset of the support
There may be a non-linear combination of features that can further subdivide the similar classes

div.h2: Begin to prep data for training with different models¶

pre.span: Create training and test splits to train classifer models, optionally include sex as a feature

ul.li: Features 3 & 2 appear to positively co-vary quite strongly (body mass index and flipper length)
Features 2 & 0 less so (flipper length and bill length)
Features 2 & 1 appear to negatively co-vary (flipper length and bill_depth)
Results shown here show here are promising in terms of their information retrieval scores
After hyperparameter tuning, we seem to find the perfect fit

div.h4: Test a k-means classifier as a sanity-check¶

ul.li: Maybe the SVM is too much for this task
Poorer results in k-means indicate difficulty distinguishing between classes purely by cluster distance
This makes sense due to similarity of the distributions
We can see the Adelie and Chinstrap clusters appear to be more difficult to distinguish
Further validates the presence of non-linear relationships between features

Given computational time, and consistency, optimized SVM appears to be the best approach.
